{
  "query": "What are the comparative outcomes of different supplementary feeding strategies for primates?",
  "relevant_summary": "Research shows varying outcomes for different supplementary feeding strategies in primates. Continuous regular feeding showed mixed results: two studies reported population increases in China and The Gambia, while two studies in Thailand and Malaysia found population declines. Continuous feeding also resulted in different diets for black-and-white ruffed lemurs compared to wild groups after one year in Madagascar. \n\nSeasonal or resource-scarce period feeding demonstrated positive survival outcomes: chimpanzees in Republic of Congo survived at least five years, wild olive baboons in Kenya survived at least 17 years after drought-period feeding, and black-and-white ruffed lemurs in Madagascar maintained wild-like diets. \n\nTime-limited feeding showed variable results: chimpanzee populations increased after two-month post-reintroduction feeding in Tanzania, while golden lion tamarin populations declined after one year of supplementation in Brazil. Survival rates were mixed across multiple studies, with some showing majority survival for various primate species including gorillas, chimpanzees, and other primates across multiple countries, while four studies found only minority survival rates. \n\nSocial context appears important: monkeys completed enrichment tasks faster when in social groups compared to feeding alone, and consumed more unfamiliar foods during initial encounters when groupmates were present.",
